This works find in AS script because the reference count is incremented in the script constructor:
static MessageBox\* ConstructMessageBox(const String& messageString, const String& titleString, XMLFile\* layoutFile, XMLFile\* styleFile)
{
    SharedPtr<MessageBox> messageBox(new MessageBox(GetScriptContext(), messageString, titleString, layoutFile, styleFile));
    if (messageBox)
        messageBox->AddRef();
    return messageBox.Get();
}

My solution to fix this was to move the add reference count in the actual MessageBox constructor and remove the one in the ConstructMessageBox()

It looks like there is no actual layer class in 2D, such as UIElement that can act as a container to hold other UI Elements as children. Instead it uses an integer layer to keep the draw order information.
1. Is it desirable to add such a class to hold other 2d drawables as children?  That way the logic of the parent/children relationship would be clearer than using layer and orderInlayer integers.
2. in Drawable2D.h, line 109
   int GetDrawOrder() const { return (layer_ << 20) + (orderInLayer_ << 10); }
   shouldn't it be 
   int GetDrawOrder() const { return (layer_ << 20) + orderInLayer_ ; }
